Continuing bird. . Got a tip-off from Shawna Dykes that the recently seen Green Heron ( seen 10- days prior - at the weir by only one observer ) , had flown southbound down the river, and was on a sandbar at Diefenbaker Park.  Shawna sent me photos an hour earlier asking me to confirm what it was. I raced down to the river within an hour of her texting me.  Initially, I spotted the bird from a high vantage point at the old cemetery that overlooks the river. By the time I got down to the park, and ground level. the bird had already moved from the waters edge, and was almost camouflaged against a pile of brush. Luckily, I got a couple of ' record shots' before it was soon flushed by people walking their dog along the shore!   This is now species number 282 for my all-time Saskatoon list :-) Amazingly, Shawna spotted Saskatoon's previous GRHE  , seen at Meewasin Park in 2019.

Observation Details: Continuing.

I watched a single scruffy juvenile attempt to forage for a few minutes at the water's edge before leaving the marsh. When I returned, that bird was gone and I spotted two more juveniles perched next to each other in a tree. Both of these birds had pink bills, while the initial bird had an orange bill already.   After observing these two for another few minutes, two adults flew into the trees and the young followed. Another young appeared and the herons were separated into groups of three and two. The parents took off again to the right and I was able to see three juveniles at once: two on a branch and one on a broken reed in the water. When I saw another bird fly in from the left, I noticed there were now two birds on the water and two in a tree. I then spotted a fifth on a branch behind the two that were already perched. I was ultimately able to watch all five juveniles at once. At one point, a Great Blue Heron flew over and all five turned and stretched their necks out to look. I wasn't sure if they were being defensive or if they'd mistaken it for one of their parents!

McCarthy Park and Medfield State Hospital
Observation Details: Six together in one view, in the marsh along the railroad tracks south of Hospital Road. Of the birds I examined closely, through my camera, only one was an adult.  I have found Green Herons in loose groups of two or three in this area before, but I was very surprised to find six-- and there may well have been one or two more.  When all but two of the birds scattered I couldn't follow every bird that took flight. The first of the posted photos is an adult.  All the rest are immatures.  The immature birds exhibit subtle differences of plumage.  The bird in the next-to-last photo, for example, seems more dully colored than the others.  It also has some conspicuous downy feathers on its crown.

Observation Details: L'individu presque adulte se promène de plus en plus loin du nid. Sa coloration n'est pas encore finale et il reste quelques filaments de duvet sur sa tête. Au nid 7-17, les deux jeunes se promènent toujours mais à proximité du nid. Un adulte vient les nourrir. Au nid près de la borne 7-16, un adulte nourrit 2 juvéniles encore recouverts de duvet. Avec de la patience et le bon angle, on peut saisir les jeunes en photos. Voici quelques clichés agrandis où l'on voit les 2 têtes des jeunes.

Observation Details: This young green heron spent over half an hour out on the tidal flats, successfully hunting for various things. Extreme slow motion movements as it crept up and suddenly extended its neck to grab a crab or other unidentifiable food item. It is very well camouflaged, hard to find again after looking at other birds. Something suddenly spooked the numerous least and western sandpipers, and the black-bellied plovers, and I looked up above their swirling forms to see a peregrine - and then saw it swoop down on the green heron, that had ignored the fuss of the other birds and looked up almost too late, freezing as it saw the falcon, then looking around realizing it was too far to fly to cover with the peregrine after it. At the last moment, the heron fell onto its back with its claws raking the air and the falcon pulled up and didn't grab it, but came around for a second pass. The heron righted itself and flew to cross the channel, landing in the water as the peregrine swooped down again and missed it as it flattened into the water and twisted around. Then the heron flew towards the rocks (towards me). The peregrine gave up at that point. In one picture you can see its crest raised in alarm - that was just after it landed on the rocks. It just stood there for about 5 minutes, then headed into the bracken. Very intense wildlife documentary.

*high; minimum without risking double counting. Mostly juvs. Once again working their way E/NE towards the big marsh and possibly beyond; stopping in trees on the way. They must all roost here? Perhaps a count at first light or dusk could produce more? At one point 10 were all visible at the same time in the trees just E of the path along Parkway pond. This was 30+ minutes after I got my count of 13, and I was able to find 11. I suspect 13 must be low because I'm fairly sure some birds had left the area prior. It appeared that some birds returned after heading in the direction of big marsh so I'm leaving it at 13. The below map is roughly the direction many Green Herons followed. Blue is areas of trees where they stopped.

Locality: McCarthy Park and Medfield State Hospital
Observation Details: Six together in one view, in the marsh along the railroad tracks south of Hospital Road. Of the birds I examined closely, through my camera, only one was an adult.  I have found Green Herons in loose groups of two or three in this area before, but I was very surprised to find six-- and there may well have been one or two more.  When all but two of the birds scattered I couldn't follow every bird that took flight. The first of the posted photos is an adult.  All the rest are immatures.  The immature birds exhibit subtle differences of plumage.  The bird in the next-to-last photo, for example, seems more dully colored than the others.  It also has some conspicuous downy feathers on its crown.

Observation Details: I watched a single scruffy juvenile attempt to forage for a few minutes at the water's edge before leaving the marsh. When I returned, that bird was gone and I spotted two more juveniles perched next to each other in a tree. Both of these birds had pink bills, while the initial bird had an orange bill already.   After observing these two for another few minutes, two adults flew into the trees and the young followed. Another young appeared and the herons were separated into groups of three and two. The parents took off again to the right and I was able to see three juveniles at once: two on a branch and one on a broken reed in the water. When I saw another bird fly in from the left, I noticed there were now two birds on the water and two in a tree. I then spotted a fifth on a branch behind the two that were already perched. I was ultimately able to watch all five juveniles at once. At one point, a Great Blue Heron flew over and all five turned and stretched their necks out to look. I wasn't sure if they were being defensive or if they'd mistaken it for one of their parents!

After observing these two for another few minutes, two adults flew into the trees and the young followed. Another young appeared and the herons were separated into groups of three and two. The parents took off again to the right and I was able to see three juveniles at once: two on a branch and one on a broken reed in the water. When I saw another bird fly in from the left, I noticed there were now two birds on the water and two in a tree. I then spotted a fifth on a branch behind the two that were already perched. I was ultimately able to watch all five juveniles at once. At one point, a Great Blue Heron flew over and all five turned and stretched their necks out to look. I wasn't sure if they were being defensive or if they'd mistaken it for one of their parents!

I watched a single scruffy juvenile attempt to forage for a few minutes at the water's edge before leaving the marsh. When I returned, that bird was gone and I spotted two more juveniles perched next to each other in a tree. Both of these birds had pink bills, while the initial bird had an orange bill already.   After observing these two for another few minutes, two adults flew into the trees and the young followed. Another young appeared and the herons were separated into groups of three and two. The parents took off again to the right and I was able to see three juveniles at once: two on a branch and one on a broken reed in the water. When I saw another bird fly in from the left, I noticed there were now two birds on the water and two in a tree. I then spotted a fifth on a branch behind the two that were already perched. I was ultimately able to watch all five juveniles at once. At one point, a Great Blue Heron flew over and all five turned and stretched their necks out to look. I wasn't sure if they were being defensive or if they'd mistaken it for one of their parents!

A Green Heron rookery begins in front of the History Museum in Forest Park at Debaliviere and Lindell and continues north, appearing to end right at Forest Park Parkway.There were eight nests on the west side of Debaliviere and one on the east side.  Most nests had young that had recently fledged and were perched on branches not far from their nests and some had ventured out a tiny bit further - a few branches or more, some were still in the nests, none seemed to be flying yet - this made them all very easy to count one by one.  I'm sure there were more than 7 adults, but that's how many we counted on at one point present, counted one by one.  A pair of adults were actively working on a new nest - we watched them start it and build the first layer.  So cool.  They seemed to be using maple trees exclusively.  This rookery is situated along a heavily trafficked road which a trolley runs along as well being situated between two super trafficked roads, with historical buildings on one end and new apartment complexes and a metrolink stop on the other.  In 2021, tipped off by Rad, we went to see what appeared to be only one nest in this area  - and two years later, 2023, it's a rocking rookery.  Super cool.  Many people walked by asking us what we were looking at.  It was easy to find the nests as there was heavy white wash on the side walk wherever there was a nest - sometimes not as heavy if the nest was higher up and the wash hit numerous branches and leaves first.  The trees all appeared to be relatively short - approximately 30' tall?  We have numerous photos.

Observation Details: Right on schedule. The area around the stormwater control pond in Lakeside Park is one of the first places this species shows up in Hampton Roads in the spring. If you'd like to learn more about the Green Heron colony here, please read "A Green Heron Colony" @ https://birdpartner.com/2020/08/28/green-heron-colony. I discovered the bird on a low branch out over the water as I was leaving the park. Contrary to what many think, these birds aren't hard to find, and they aren't skittish. The bird spent time resting, but also spent a fair amount of time preening, which is understandable.

The green heron's disappeared into the foliage and I could not get any further observation in the meantime the yellow crowned night heron remained in place

Green Heron infrequent on this property as far as I have seen the past 4 years. First observation of more than 1 individual. Initially, I witnessed 2 fly languidly from smallest pond up near road into opposite sides of tall tree over largest pond, both perched out on a bare area at outer edges. Both then dropped into large pond. One was on same branch about 20 minutes later. Impossible to see them in pond as cattails and dogbane form a thick wall and/or hedge between 4 and 7 feet tall. I walked by same area about 30 minutes later and a passing car startled one back up to favored branch again and I was at a good angle for pictures as morning light hit it. Moved about on limb for about 10 minutes, defecated, moved around for another minute and flew off, dropping into smallest pond up by road once more.

Observation Details: The Male adult was hanging around the pond and flew of towards Snug Harbor marsh. Shortly after, the female came out of a tree and flew the same way. One of the juveniles took off after the female. Two other juveniles came out and explored the dock, bulkhead and shore. Then one of the juveniles took off towards the Sealevel marsh across the bay. The Male adult returned and started hanging around the pond. Then another juvenile took off, flying south towards the Sealevel marsh (and oyster beds). It looks like the juveniles are beginning to disperse for foraging in the marshes around Nelson Bay.
